<br>c.	<b>Anabaptist</b> (pacifist)
<br>d.	<b>Liberty of Conscience</b>
<br>The Liberty of Conscience view is developed and applied in a practical way in <i>Bible and Government: Public Policy from a Christian Perspective</i>.  In the same way that Theonomy is the logical outcome of a Presbyterian and postmillenarian theology, Liberty of Conscience is the logical outcome of a Baptist theology (whether premillenarian or amillenarian). Als see Dr. Cobin's book <i>Christian Theology of Public Policy: Highlighting the American Experience</i> for a fuller treatment of the four views.</FONT></FONT>
</P>

